AttributeValuesData.AttributeValue: The Green Ash is one of the most ubiquitous trees in Minnesota, especially in the southern portions of the state. It is most abundant on low river terraces, floodplains, and in a variety of moist habitats. It is tolerant of flooding and drought and is often planted to revegetate lands after strip mining. Since the onset of Dutch elm disease, the green ash has been heavily used as a replacement for the American elm in urban landscapes across the U.S. Unfortunately, now the green ash is under attack by the emerald ash borer and cities in Minnesota are making plans to manage their invested trees.
Ashy-gray to gray-brown, fissures make a diamond pattern
Unisexual with male and female flowers on separate trees. Purplish, produced on old wood just below new shoot.
1-seeded samara, 1-2" long, narrowly obovate; wing extends from middle of narrow, cylindrical seed
Opposite, pinnately compound, up to 12" long. 5-9 leaflets, 2-5" long, 1-2" wide, ovate to oblong-lanceolate, lustrous medium to dark green.
Opposite compound leaves, adaptability and tolerance to a variety of different environments, threatened by the emerald ash borer.
